DOCKER FILE :
------------------------------------------
ðŸ§¨ FROM : specifies the base image 
ðŸ§¨ LABEL : LABEL is used whenever someone or some tool needs to read information about the image â€” during inspection, automation, registries, and organizing images.
    LABEL project="inventory-service"
    LABEL app="payment-api"
    LABEL team="backend"
ðŸ§¨WORKDIR :
   Sets the working directory for subsequent commands.
ðŸ§¨ COPY : copy the files 
ðŸ§¨ ADD : 
    Like COPY, but also supports URLs and auto-extracts tar archives.
    ADD https://example.com/file.tar.gz /tmp/
ðŸ§¨ ARG : 
    Used only during image build.
    Not available inside the running container.
    Good for build-time options (e.g., versions).
    
    Example:
    ARG VERSION=1.0
    After build â†’ VERSION is gone.
ðŸ§¨ENV :
    Available during build and inside the running container.
    Stays permanently in the final image.
    Good for runtime configuration.
    Example:
    ENV MODE=production
    Inside container â†’ $MODE is available. 
ðŸ§¨ RUN :
    Executes a command during build to create a new image layer.
    RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y python3
ðŸ§¨ EXPOSE :
      Documents which ports the container listens on.
      EXPOSE 8080
ðŸ§¨ VOLUME : 
      Creates or marks a mount point for persistent storage.
      VOLUME ["/data"]
ðŸ§¨ USER
      Sets user for subsequent commands.
      USER appuser
ðŸ§¨ ENTRYPOINT :
      Defines the main command that always runs.
      Harder to override.
      Example:
      ENTRYPOINT ["python"]
ðŸ§¨ CMD : 
      Provides default arguments to ENTRYPOINT
      â€” OR becomes the command if no ENTRYPOINT is set.
      Easy to override using docker run.
      Example:
      CMD ["app.py"]

In one sentence:
ENTRYPOINT = main program, CMD = default arguments (or fallback command).


1. ARG â†’ build-time only
ARG is like a variable used while building the image.
You can override it during docker build with --build-arg.
After the image is built, the ARG value disappears.

The running container does not know about it.
Example:
ARG environment=prod
RUN echo "Building for $environment"
Build with:
docker build --build-arg environment=dev .
Output: Building for dev
Container wonâ€™t have $environment set.

2. ENV â†’ runtime variable
ENV sets a variable inside the container, available at runtime.
You can override it when running the container using -e or --env.
Example:
ENV ENVIRONMENT=prod
Run with override:
docker run -e ENVIRONMENT=dev myimage
Inside container: $ENVIRONMENT = dev

DOCKER COMMANDS :

| Command                              | Description                                               |
| ------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker build -t <name>:<tag> .`     | Build an image from a Dockerfile in the current directory |
| `docker images` or `docker image ls` | List all local images                                     |
| `docker rmi <image>`                 | Remove an image                                           |
| `docker pull <image>`                | Download an image from Docker Hub or registry             |
| `docker push <image>`                | Upload an image to a registry                             |
| `docker tag <source> <target>`       | Tag an image for pushing to a registry                    |
| `docker history <image>`             | Show image build history                                  |

| Command                                 | Description                             |
| --------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| `docker run <image>`                    | Run a container from an image           |
| `docker run -it <image> /bin/bash`      | Run container interactively with shell  |
| `docker ps`                             | List running containers                 |
| `docker ps -a`                          | List all containers (including stopped) |
| `docker stop <container>`               | Stop a running container                |
| `docker start <container>`              | Start a stopped container               |
| `docker restart <container>`            | Restart a container                     |
| `docker rm <container>`                 | Remove a container                      |
| `docker logs <container>`               | Show container logs                     |
| `docker exec -it <container> /bin/bash` | Enter a running container               |
| `docker inspect <container>`            | Detailed info about container           |

| Command                                    | Description                       |
| ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------- |
| `docker volume create <name>`              | Create a volume                   |
| `docker volume ls`                         | List volumes                      |
| `docker volume rm <name>`                  | Remove a volume                   |
| `docker run -v <volume>:<container_path>`  | Mount volume in container         |
| `docker cp <container>:<path> <host_path>` | Copy files from container to host |
| `docker cp <host_path> <container>:<path>` | Copy files from host to container |

| Command                          | Description                    |
| -------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `docker network ls`              | List networks                  |
| `docker network create <name>`   | Create a network               |
| `docker network rm <name>`       | Remove a network               |
| `docker run --network <network>` | Connect container to a network |

| Command                  | Description                                                 |
| ------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker system df`       | Show disk usage of Docker images, containers, volumes       |
| `docker system prune`    | Remove stopped containers, unused networks, dangling images |
| `docker container prune` | Remove all stopped containers                               |
| `docker image prune`     | Remove unused/dangling images                               |
| `docker volume prune`    | Remove unused volumes                                       |

| Command                                    | Description                              |
| ------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| `docker build --build-arg <ARG>=<value> .` | Override ARG values at build-time        |
| `docker build -t <name>:<tag> .`           | Give image a name and tag while building |
| `docker build --no-cache .`                | Build without using cache                |

| Command                            | Description                                   |
| ---------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| `docker run -d <image>`            | Run container in detached mode (background)   |
| `docker run -p <host>:<container>` | Map ports from container to host              |
| `docker run -e <VAR>=<value>`      | Set environment variable in container         |
| `docker run --name <name> <image>` | Give a container a custom name                |
| `docker run --rm <image>`          | Automatically remove container after it stops |

| Command                                   | Description                                      |
| ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `docker-compose up`                       | Start all services defined in docker-compose.yml |
| `docker-compose up -d`                    | Start services in detached mode                  |
| `docker-compose down`                     | Stop and remove containers, networks, volumes    |
| `docker-compose build`                    | Build images defined in docker-compose.yml       |
| `docker-compose logs`                     | Show logs for all services                       |
| `docker-compose exec <service> /bin/bash` | Enter a running service container                |

| Command                                   | Description                                          |
| ----------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker buildx build`                     | Advanced build command with multi-platform support   |
| `docker save <image> -o <file.tar>`       | Save an image to a tar file for export               |
| `docker load -i <file.tar>`               | Load an image from a tar file                        |
| `docker history --no-trunc <image>`       | Show full history of layers in an image              |
| `docker commit <container> <new_image>`   | Save the current state of a container as a new image |
| `docker export <container> -o <file.tar>` | Export a containerâ€™s filesystem to a tar file        |


| Command                                                    | Description                                                    |
| ---------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker attach <container>`                                | Attach your terminal to a running container                    |
| `docker top <container>`                                   | Show processes running inside a container                      |
| `docker stats`                                             | Real-time resource usage (CPU, memory, network) for containers |
| `docker port <container>`                                  | Show port mappings for a container                             |
| `docker update --cpu=<value> --memory=<value> <container>` | Dynamically update resource limits for a running container     |
| `docker rename <old_name> <new_name>`                      | Rename a container                                             |
| `docker pause <container>` / `docker unpause <container>`  | Pause and resume a containerâ€™s processes                       |


| Command                                           | Description                                      |
| ------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `docker network inspect <network>`                | Show detailed info about a network               |
| `docker network connect <network> <container>`    | Connect a running container to a network         |
| `docker network disconnect <network> <container>` | Disconnect a container from a network            |
| `docker run --network=host`                       | Use host network mode for performance or testing |


| Command                                         | Description                                                                 |
| ----------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker volume inspect <volume>`                | Show detailed info about a volume                                           |
| `docker run -v <host_path>:<container_path>:ro` | Mount volume as read-only                                                   |
| `docker diff <container>`                       | Show filesystem changes in a container since it started                     |
| `docker system df -v`                           | Detailed view of disk usage by images, containers, volumes, and build cache |


| Command                                                   | Description                                                  |
| --------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `docker logs -f <container>`                              | Follow logs in real time                                     |
| `docker logs --tail <n> <container>`                      | Show only the last n lines of logs                           |
| `docker events`                                           | Stream real-time Docker events (container start, stop, etc.) |
| `docker inspect --format '{{.State.Status}}' <container>` | Get specific info using Go templates                         |


| Command                            | Description                                                                |
| ---------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `docker trust sign <image>`        | Sign an image for content trust                                            |
| `docker trust inspect <image>`     | Verify image signature                                                     |
| `docker system prune -a --volumes` | Aggressive cleanup of all unused images, containers, networks, and volumes |




